<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>Advertisers and marketers need to adapt to new methods and technologies=
 for tracking and targeting users across different websites and devices tha=
t help build trust with users.</li>



<li>Google and Meta have introduced Enhanced Conversions and Advanced Match=
ing, respectively, to improve ad targeting and conversion tracking using ha=
shed first-party data.&nbsp;</li>



<li>The two technologies raise serious privacy concerns connected with the =
potential for reidentifying users, lack of proper user consent and Google=
=E2=80=99s and Meta=E2=80=99s ability to reuse the data for their purposes.=
</li>



<li>Companies should consider other options that don=E2=80=99t breach user =
privacy, such as contextual targeting for ads or privacy-compliant analytic=
s with vendors like Piwik PRO.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>



<p>Privacy regulations such as GDPR and CCPA have significantly changed how=
 companies can track and measure user interactions online. Additionally, th=
e rise of adblockers and browser tracking restrictions limit the use of thi=
rd-party cookies on the web.&nbsp;<br><br>Users are blocking and deleting c=
ookies due to a lack of trust in the AdTech industry and what happens with =
their data. To build trust, companies must adjust their data collection pro=
cesses to be transparent and respect users=E2=80=99 <a href=3D"https://piwi=
k.pro/glossary/consent/">consent</a> choices. Advertisers and marketers nee=
d to adapt to new methods and technologies for tracking and targeting users=
 across different websites and devices that help build trust with users.<br=
><br>To mitigate the impact of these privacy-facing developments, tech gian=
ts have created their own solutions =E2=80=93 Google has introduced Enhance=
d Conversions, while Meta has launched Advanced Matching. They aim to enhan=
ce conversion tracking by leveraging first-party data, earning them the nic=
kname =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://brianclifton.com/blog/2024/02/26/3p-cooki=
es-v-benign-data-v-cookies-on-steroids/">cookies on steroids</a>=E2=80=9C. =
However, recent guidance from the Federal Trade Commission (FTC) suggests t=
hat these solutions are not as privacy-compliant as they claim. Using them =
comes with significant privacy risks: once the data is captured, it is out =
of the user=E2=80=99s control, giving Google and Meta unlimited possibiliti=
es to use it to their benefit.&nbsp;<br><br>Today, we will explore Google=
=E2=80=99s and Meta=E2=80=99s initiatives more closely, looking into how th=
ey work and how privacy-compliant they actually are. We will also discuss o=
ther solutions that companies can utilize to combine privacy compliance wit=
h effective leveraging of data.</p>


